    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-d, Ah-i). Most stands occur around San Francisco Bay (Atwater et al. 1979, Duke et al. 1999, Baye et al. 2000, Rana Creek Habitat Restoration 2002, Grewell et al. 2007) and around San Pablo Bay as far north as the mouth of the Petaluma Creek. Others occur around Monterey Bay.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Al). The most inland, lowest-salinity stands are probably at the western edge of Suisun Marsh near Benicia Bridge (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Ak-l). Stands at Bolinas Lagoon, Drakes Bay, and Tomales Bay lack <i>Spartina alternifolia</i> (Atwater et al. 1979, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). Northerly stands of <i>S. foliosa</i> are at Bodega Bay; however, reports outside of its native range include Humboldt Bay and Crescent City marshes.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb, Bd, Bf-g, Bj). Stands occur in low marshes, along creeks, and up to the marsh plain in Santa Barbara Co. and other coastal counties in the section. The largest stands occur in the marshes at Anaheim Bay, Bolsa Chica, Mission Bay, Mugu Lagoon, San Diego Bay, Tijuana Estuary, and Upper Newport Bay (Purer 1942, Vogl 1966, Peinado et al. 1994, Grewell et al. 2007). Small stands also occur in the tidal marsh at the Ballona Wetlands Wildlife Area.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Unmanaged tidal wetlands are rare in the state because of a history of diking, dredging, levees, landfills, and intensive wildlife management. Hybridization with <i>Spartina alterniflora </i>is the largest threat to central California marshes with mudflat loss, converting areas to monotypic stands of the hybrid (Ayres et al. 2007). Ecologists need to consider species richness as an important component in restoration (Callaway et al. 2002, Zedler et al. 2001). </div>
</div>

    

    

